'''Philip E. Stieg''' (born July 1952) is an American academic [[physician]] and [[neurosurgeon]].

==Early life==

Stieg was born in [[Milwaukee]], WI,<ref>''http://www.societyns.org/society/bio.aspx?MemberID=6136''</ref> the third son of Betty and Edwin Stieg.  He attended parochial schools for his primary and secondary education, and then enrolled at the [[University of Wisconsin–Madison]] (UW) in 1970.

==University & Graduate Education==

Stieg earned a B.S. degree in [[Zoology]] from UW in 1974.<ref>''http://www.uwalumni.com/default.asp'', Search=Philip Stieg</ref>  Philip pursued graduate studies in [[neuroanatomy]] & [[neuroscience]] at [[Albany Medical College]]/[[Union University]], and was awarded a [[Ph.D.]] in 1980.  He then attended medical school at the [[Medical College of Wisconsin]] in Milwaukee, completing his [[M.D.]] degree in 1983.<ref>''http://nyp.org/news/hospital/stieg-neurosurgery.html''</ref>

Stieg was a resident in [[general surgery]] and [[neurosurgery]] at the [[University of Texas]]-Southwestern Medical School & [[Parkland Memorial Hospital]], under the direction of Duke Samson and Hunt Batjer. Thereafter, he did a fellowship in cell transplantation for restorative neurological function at the [[Karolinska Institute]] in [[Stockholm]], Sweden.<ref>''http://www.wamc.org/stiegbio.html''</ref>

==Professional career==

Stieg joined the faculty of the [[Harvard Medical School]], [[Brigham and Women's Hospital]], and [[Children's Hospital of Boston]] in Boston, MA in 1989, after completion of his postgraduate training.<ref>''Op cit''., Ref. 1.</ref>  He developed research and clinical interests in cerebral protection and restorative function, neural transplantation, neuronal regeneration after stroke, [[cerebrovascular]] surgery, and surgery of the skull base.<ref>Greenfield JP, Ayuso-Sacido A, Schwartz TH, Pannullo S, Souweidane M, '''Stieg PE''', Boockvar JA: Use of human neural tissue for the generation of progenitors.  ''Neurosurgery'' 2008; 62: 21-37.</ref><ref>Fraser JF, Riina H, Mitra N, Gobin YP, Simon AS, '''Stieg PE''': Treatment of ruptured intracranial aneurysms: looking to the past to register the future.  ''Neurosurgery'' 2006; 59: 1157-1166.</ref><ref>Janardhan V, Biondi A, Riina HA, Sanelli PC, '''Stieg PE''', Gobin YP: Vasospasm in aneurysmal subarachnoid hemorrhage: diagnosis, prevention, and management.  ''Neuroimaging Clin N Am'' 2006; 16: 483-496.</ref><ref>'''Stieg PE''', Friedlander RM, Loeffler JS, Alexander E III: Endoscopic transsphenoidal pituitary surgery with intraoperative magnetic resonance imaging.  ''Neurosurgery'' 2006; 58 (Suppl): S44-S51.</ref> His investigative studies have focused on understanding the mechanisms of injury in the [[central nervous system]] after trauma, as well as mechanisms of cell-membrane transport and their implications after traumatic brain injury.<ref>''Op cit''., Ref. 3.</ref><ref>Park KI, Himes BT, '''Stieg PE''', et al.: Neural stem cells may be uniquely suited for combined gene therapy and cell replacement: evidence from engraftment of neurotrophin-3-expressing stem cells in hypoxic-ischemic brain injury.  ''Exp Neurol'' 2006; 199: 179-190.</ref>

In November 2000, Stieg was named Professor & Chair of the Department of Neurosurgery at Cornell-[[Weill Medical College]] and [[New York-Presbyterian Medical Center]] in New York City. He has continued to be active in clinical practice, research, and medical education since then.  Stieg is the recipient of several awards and honors, including citations in "''[[Who's Who]] in Health and Medical Services''" and "''The Best Doctors in America''".<ref>''Op cit''., Ref. 3.</ref>  He has authored over 65 peer-reviewed publications in the medical literature,<ref>''http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/sites/entrez/'', Search = stieg pe</ref> and he has co-edited a textbook entitled "''[[Intracranial]] [[Arteriovenous Malformation]]s''".<ref>'''Stieg''' PE, Batjer HH, Samson DS (Eds): '''''Intracranial Arteriovenous Malformations'''''. Informa Healthcare, New York, NY, 2007. '''ISBN 0824709934'''</ref>

